label chapter15:

    # [Scene: Community Shelter & Town Hall | Morning — One Week After Petition Submission]

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Brass and strings surge in a bright, urgent rhythm — celebratory but taut]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant gull cries; camera shutters click as someone photographs the mayor signing documents]
    "You remember the night you chose Elias' plan like the shape of a held breath — concise diagrams, community training modules, an ask that sounded reasonable even to people who mistrust promises. Today, the ask sits"
    "on the mayor's desk in a stack of legalese and signatures. The petition you carried out of the shelter is no longer just ink on paper; it's a lever, and for the first time in months"
    "you feel it move under your hands."
    show mayor_sofa_lvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_sofa_lvarez "This hybrid policy... it isn't perfect. It asks us to be bold and cautious at the same time. We fund living-shore pilots, and we create zones for co-development with Duval — but we build hard protections only where absolutely necessary, and with community oversight."
    "You listen to the words until they become something you can hold. There's a tremor of tension under the applause; some faces in the crowd breathe relief, others count losses. That's the shape of compromise — uneven, human, alive."
    show elias_stone at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_stone "You did it. You translated the anger into something they could sign."
    show maya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We did it,"

    mayor_sofa_lvarez "We'll form an oversight board with community representatives, Professor Hale will monitor outcomes, and Duval will open quarterly reports to public review. We will also fund training programs to employ local stewards."
    hide mayor_sofa_lvarez
    show amaya_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_chen "And the cove? The industrial strip?"
    hide elias_stone
    show mayor_sofa_lvarez at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_sofa_lvarez "We negotiated to cede a narrow industrial strip for reclaimed fill — to keep critical commerce running — but it's designated and monitored. There are conditions."
    "You feel the high, bright ache of victory and the gravity of what you've conceded at the same time. The win tastes like fried fish and thermos coffee — celebratory and practical — and like a"
    "bruise behind your ribs that says some places were given up so others could live."
    hide maya_reyes
    show lito_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    lito_reyes "You kept most of the houses, May. That's huge."
    "You reach for his hand without thinking; it warms your palm, callused and steady. He squeezes, and the relief in his face makes your resolve feel less like a solitary burden."

    menu:
        "Raise your thermos and toast the volunteers":
            "You lift your thermos high. Around you, neighbors mimic the motion — battered tins and chipped mugs — and for a moment the air is all warmth and laughter, the kind that stitches a community from small, shared gestures."
        "Pull Elias aside and whisper about next grant deadlines":
            "You take Elias' sleeve and tug him away from the crowd. He laughs softly, then listens as you sketch timelines in the margin of your notebook; the practical plans slide into place like gears finding teeth."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Greenhouse Lab | Late Afternoon — Two Months Later]
    hide amaya_chen
    hide mayor_sofa_lvarez
    hide lito_reyes

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussion quickens with a hopeful melody; a heartbeat under the rooftop chatter]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Drip-irrigation ticks, sneakers on wet concrete, the rustle of seed packets]
    "The greenhouse hums like a heart. Training sessions run back-to-back; neighbors come with coffee and questions, with children in tow and hands that need work. You're teaching someone to cut Spartina plugs when Elias calls your name with a grin and a rolled plan under his arm."
    show elias_stone at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_stone "They approved the grant for the community training curriculum."
    "You stop mid-cutting, salt in your scalp and potting soil under your nails. The news lands like a warm tide."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Already? That's—"

    elias_stone "They liked your testimony. Your map made it concrete."
    "You and Elias Stone stand close among the trays. He leans in, the scent of compost and sea between you."

    elias_stone "I'll split my time. Grants, paperwork, the city meetings — and here when I can. We'll figure out a schedule."

    maya_reyes "We will."
    show professor_rowan_hale at center:
        zoom 0.7

    professor_rowan_hale "Maya, the accretion models are matching early results. Your planting grids are accelerating sediment capture at a measurable rate."

    maya_reyes "We need more sensors along the industrial edge, though. The fill will change flows."

    professor_rowan_hale "I've got a student team lined up. This work will be replicable."
    "Momentum builds and multiplies. Every success breeds more work: grants to write, training sessions to hold, oversight meetings to attend. The days feel packed with purpose; the nights thin out with urgency. The arousal in your"
    "chest is no longer only adrenaline — it's a sustained, high-energy commitment that hums deeper than panic: a fierce, resolute cadence toward repair."

    menu:
        "Take the late shift teaching tide-monitoring to teenagers":
            "You stay. The teens arrive with skepticism and skateboard shoes, but by the end they're measuring with you, laughing at the rhythm of the tideclock; one writes 'future steward' on a sticky note and sticks it to the corkboard."
        "Go home early and draft the community's quarterly report with Elias":
            "You leave the greenhouse in Elias' hands. Back at the flat, you two write late into the night, annotating photos, translating science into plain language. The report reads like a promise made and kept."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues."
    # [Scene: Partially Restored Tidal Fringe | Dawn — Six Months After Policy Implementation]
    hide elias_stone
    hide maya_reyes
    hide professor_rowan_hale

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A swelling, cathartic orchestral surge — high strings and a confident brass line]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The marsh is alive — reed whisper, distant machinery throttling down, neighbor voices mingling with gulls]
    "You stand at the lip of where water meets earth, boots sinking into the soft, promising mud. Around you, a crew of neighbors and trainees plant Spartina and cordgrass with practiced motions that have become almost"
    "ceremonial. The work is physical and immediate; every push of a plug into mud is both a repair and a vote for a future you want to keep."
    show amaya_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_chen "Watch spacing—three fingers between plugs! That gives room for rhizomes!"
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Got it."
    show camille_duval at center:
        zoom 0.7

    camille_duval "You've done well here, Ms. Reyes. We will monitor the industrial zone closely; our fill strategy is designed to offset risk for the port workers and small manufacturers."

    maya_reyes "Transparency will be required. Oversight will be public. The restoration can't be a token while concrete swallows what remains."

    camille_duval "Agreed. My team will report quarterly. The board will have a seat — more than one, as negotiated."
    "Her words are crisp, but something in her voice hints at genuine calculation, not malice. It feels like an uneasy truce — a technical, brittle accord that still opens the possibility for accountability."
    hide amaya_chen
    show mayor_sofa_lvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_sofa_lvarez "We will fund an apprenticeship program for local stewards, and Duval commits to hiring from within the community for their monitoring roles. This isn't charity — it's investment."
    hide maya_reyes
    show lito_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lito_reyes "So we get work and keep the cove. Not bad."
    hide camille_duval
    show maya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Not bad,"
    hide mayor_sofa_lvarez
    show professor_rowan_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    professor_rowan_hale "Early sedimentation rates are promising. With continued planting and community stewardship, the living-shore can absorb energy that a wall would have reflected catastrophically."

    maya_reyes "We keep people here, not just properties,"
    "The arousal in the air lifts to a peak now: legal sessions, community oversight, training rosters, grant approvals — each a drumbeat. You feel fatigue, yes, but radiating through it is a kind of electric joy. The work is hard, messy, and immediate; it requires bodies, patience, and stubborn love."
    hide lito_reyes
    show elias_stone at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_stone "Come on,' he urges, handing you a plug. 'Finish this row with me."
    "You take the plug, press it home, shoulder to shoulder. Your movements sync like a practiced dance. He brushes mud from your cheek without thinking, thumb gentle."

    elias_stone "We keep showing up. One tide at a time."

    maya_reyes "One tide at a time."

    menu:
        "Shout to the crew, 'Let's make this a pattern—we plant every weekend!'":
            "Your voice carries. Heads lift and someone cheers. A spontaneous cadence forms and soon the row becomes a communal rhythm — stamping, laughing, reciting counts."
        "Lean in and tell Elias you want to formalize a training school for stewards":
            "He meets your eyes and nods slowly. Plans unfold in shorthand between you two — curriculum, certification, a small seed of institutional permanence."

